00:41:06.200 --> 00:41:07.116
-Yeah, you're welcome.

00:41:07.116 --> 00:41:09.120
-I recently was at a
conference in New York

00:41:09.120 --> 00:41:11.710
where I watched the
scientist and attorneys

00:41:11.710 --> 00:41:13.770
for the prosecutor
and the defense

00:41:13.770 --> 00:41:18.150
literally scream at each other
about the use of low copy DNA.

00:41:18.150 --> 00:41:19.140
-That was in New York?

00:41:19.140 --> 00:41:19.920
-There was in New York.

00:41:19.920 --> 00:41:20.650
-Yeah, of course.

00:41:20.650 --> 00:41:22.150
-Just curious what
your thoughts are

00:41:22.150 --> 00:41:23.970
about the use of low copy DNA.

00:41:23.970 --> 00:41:26.480
-Well, low copy means
two different things.

00:41:26.480 --> 00:41:28.350
The original meaning
of that meant

00:41:28.350 --> 00:41:30.347
we did extra rounds of PCR.

00:41:30.347 --> 00:41:32.680
And in that case, you actually
see what we call drop-in.

00:41:32.680 --> 00:41:35.590
And all the drop-in
is, is DNA that's

00:41:35.590 --> 00:41:38.250
just kind of floating
around or in the glove

00:41:38.250 --> 00:41:40.280
when you buy-- on the
glove or in the tube

00:41:40.280 --> 00:41:43.467
that you don't see with these
normal 28 rounds or 30 rounds.

00:41:43.467 --> 00:41:45.550
But when you do the extra
rounds, you get drop-in.

00:41:45.550 --> 00:41:47.679
But low template
DNA, which probably

00:41:47.679 --> 00:41:49.220
is something they
were arguing about,

00:41:49.220 --> 00:41:52.440
is when you have very low levels
like in Amanda Knox's case,

00:41:52.440 --> 00:41:55.320
you'll get different results
in some of those cases.

00:41:55.320 --> 00:41:58.430
And so in New York
at the OCME, they

00:41:58.430 --> 00:42:01.170
were saying, oh, if you get the
result two out of three times,

00:42:01.170 --> 00:42:03.060
you can report it.

00:42:03.060 --> 00:42:05.871
And when I did a
case in London, they

00:42:05.871 --> 00:42:07.370
said, well, it has
to be repeatable.

00:42:07.370 --> 00:42:08.703
And I thought, that makes sense.

00:42:08.703 --> 00:42:10.180
A repeatable result is reliable.

00:42:10.180 --> 00:42:11.720
And then I looked
at their records.

00:42:11.720 --> 00:42:12.994
They did, like, 10 tests.

00:42:12.994 --> 00:42:14.410
Two of them were
what they wanted.

00:42:14.410 --> 00:42:15.500
They picked the two.

00:42:15.500 --> 00:42:17.120
They called it repeatable.

00:42:17.120 --> 00:42:19.570
So I think there's
a lot of problems

00:42:19.570 --> 00:42:21.070
with some of those techniques.

00:42:21.070 --> 00:42:23.390
But frankly, that
bar keeps moving.

00:42:23.390 --> 00:42:25.460
As we get down to
single cell resolution,

00:42:25.460 --> 00:42:28.420
it won't be as much
of a question anymore.

00:42:28.420 --> 00:42:31.280
So we keep lowering the bar
of what low template is.

00:42:31.280 --> 00:42:32.930
So, yes, it should be used.

00:42:32.930 --> 00:42:36.090
Yes, there are problems.

00:42:36.090 --> 00:42:37.280
-Hi, I'm Faye Flam.

00:42:37.280 --> 00:42:39.730
I'm a journalist with
MIT Technology Review

00:42:39.730 --> 00:42:44.570
and I was intrigued by these
cases where there are mixtures

00:42:44.570 --> 00:42:47.600
and the statistics looked
good, where there was like a 1

00:42:47.600 --> 00:42:49.540
in 2000 chance it was wrong.

00:42:49.540 --> 00:42:51.310
Is the problem there
that the person

00:42:51.310 --> 00:42:55.110
was the 1 in 2000 or the problem
that people are screwing up

00:42:55.110 --> 00:42:58.640
the numbers, that they're
making statistical errors?

00:42:58.640 --> 00:43:01.300
-The problem is that there
are several good methods

00:43:01.300 --> 00:43:03.070
to do statistics
and they produce

00:43:03.070 --> 00:43:05.310
extremely variable results.

00:43:05.310 --> 00:43:08.780
So when I say good, they're
based on mathematics.

00:43:08.780 --> 00:43:12.450
All the statisticians agree
they're good, robust methods.

00:43:12.450 --> 00:43:14.950
But you get 10 to
the 10 differences.

00:43:14.950 --> 00:43:16.940
And then you get labs
that will exclude.

00:43:16.940 --> 00:43:19.350
Most labs are still
applying rules of thumb.

00:43:19.350 --> 00:43:21.410
If there's only one
allele, we won't call it.

00:43:21.410 --> 00:43:23.170
Utah told me there
had to be at least two

00:43:23.170 --> 00:43:24.880
that weren't found
to exclude somebody.

00:43:24.880 --> 00:43:27.820
They all have these rules of
thumb that they're applying.

00:43:27.820 --> 00:43:31.270
So the statistics are helpful.

00:43:31.270 --> 00:43:34.010
But also, I think our idea
about these statistics is wrong.

00:43:34.010 --> 00:43:38.420
If I say 1 in 5,000 in
a Boston crime, that

00:43:38.420 --> 00:43:41.405
means there's 1,000 people
in Boston who might--

00:43:41.405 --> 00:43:44.140
who are I match, a
definite match, right?

00:43:44.140 --> 00:43:46.880
And so if you think of it
in terms of epidemiology

00:43:46.880 --> 00:43:49.060
or in terms of medical
testing, that's

00:43:49.060 --> 00:43:53.090
a false positive
rate of 999 to 1.

00:43:53.090 --> 00:43:58.720
So for every one person in a
1 in 5,000 match in Boston,

00:43:58.720 --> 00:44:02.617
for every right one,
there are 999 wrong ones.

00:44:02.617 --> 00:44:04.200
And it doesn't mean
we don't use that,

00:44:04.200 --> 00:44:07.110
but you have to start
giving a better perspective.

00:44:07.110 --> 00:44:11.130
Because jurors hear 1 in 1,000,
1 in 10,000, 1 in a million,

00:44:11.130 --> 00:44:12.690
and they think it's over.

00:44:12.690 --> 00:44:15.550
They don't hear
numbers like that.

00:44:15.550 --> 00:44:17.910
They hear 50-50.

00:44:17.910 --> 00:44:19.087
It's 20% chance.

00:44:19.087 --> 00:44:21.170
When they hear those kind
of overwhelming numbers,

00:44:21.170 --> 00:44:22.630
they generally convict.

00:44:22.630 --> 00:44:25.590
-Thank you.

